dcterms:description: The Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) is a public-private partnership aimed at testing whether serial magnetic resonance imaging, positron emission tomography, other biological markers, and clinical and neuropsychological assessments can be combined to measure the progression of mild cognitive impairment and early Alzheimer’s disease.
dcterms:title: Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI)

dcterms:description: The Alzheimer’s Disease Prediction Of Longitudinal Evolution (TADPOLE) challenge dataset is composed of data from the three ADNI phases ADNI 1, ADNI GO, and ADNI 2, including roughly 1,500 biomarkers acquired from 1,737 subjects during 12,741 visits at 22 distinct time points between 2003 and 2017.
dcterms:title: The Alzheimer’s Disease Prediction Of Longitudinal Evolution (TADPOLE) challenge dataset

dcterms:description: MRI biomarkers refer to volumetric magnetic resonance imaging biomarkers used for modeling the progression of Alzheimer’s disease.
dcterms:title: MRI biomarkers

dcterms:description: Various MRI biomarkers include the volumes of ventricles, hippocampus, whole brain, fusiform, middle temporal gyrus, and entorhinal cortex used in the context of Alzheimer’s disease progression modeling.
dcterms:title: Various MRI biomarkers
